## What's covered

**Email** — RFC validation via `email-validator`, NFKC normalization, IDN/punycode handling, lowercase canonical key, disposable-domain blocklist, control/bidi char stripping, length cap.

**Username** — length bounds, strict charset regex (start/end alphanumeric), repeated-separator rejection, reserved-word list, offensive-word filter, homoglyph/mixed-script detection, NFKC normalization, casefold for uniqueness.

**Password** — min 12 / max 128 (DoS cap; argon2 is unbounded so the cap matters), 3-of-4 character classes, common-password list, no-username/email-substring, repeated-char and sequence detection, breached-password check via HIBP k-anonymity (opt-in, fail-open), **Argon2id** hashing with tuned cost.

**Security** — parameterized SQL everywhere, Argon2id (never MD5/SHA), token-bucket rate limiting before expensive work, account-enumeration prevention (identical 202 response + dummy-hash timing equalization + `secrets.compare_digest`), control/bidi/zero-width sanitization, output-escaping note (escape on render, not storage).

**Edge cases** — duplicate detection, concurrent-signup race handled by lock + `UNIQUE` constraint + `IntegrityError` fallback, whitespace/unicode normalization, all-errors-at-once `422` responses, correct status codes (202/422/429/500).

## Notes for production hardening
- **CSRF**: not applicable to a token-auth JSON API; if you serve this from cookie-authenticated browser sessions, add a CSRF token / `SameSite` + double-submit check (FastAPI has no built-in — add `starlette-csrf` or equivalent).
- Move the rate limiter and disposable/common-password/offensive lists to **Redis + maintained datasets**; the in-process versions reset on restart and don't span workers.
- Put this behind HTTPS and set security headers (HSTS, CSP) at the proxy.
- The `_db_lock` serializes writes (fine for SQLite/single process). With Postgres, drop the lock and rely on the `UNIQUE` constraint + `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT`.

